      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re your ''Harvesting Poverty'' editorials (July 20 and 22):</p>
        <p>Developing countries often criticize countries in the developed world for their high subsidies and trade barriers that make it almost impossible to compete.</p>
        <p>As a Foreign Service retiree who spent most of my time in Latin America, I am appalled by the continuing poverty and high rates of unemployment there.</p>
        <p>Free trade, which the administration is so eager to promote, only improves the standard of living of the middle and upper classes.</p>
        <p>Right now, there is active opposition to the attempt to form a Free Trade Zone of the Americas.</p>
        <p>This administration ignores Latin America except where the drug trade or free-market initiatives are concerned. Eradication of poverty will never happen this way.</p>
        <p>JO ALBRIGHT  New York, July 22, 2003</p>
      </block>
